WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.640
My name is Mike, and I'm here to talk to you today about interactive graphics in R.

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:18.000
A little bit about me, I code in R for a living, and I believe R can be fun.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.000
What do I mean by fun?

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I mean things like including kittens in ggplots, running destructive physics simulations, and

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.600
currently I'm experimenting with voxel rendering.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:38.360
There is fun to be had in R, and today I'd like to share with you such a discovery.

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:43.740
And that is, with careful use of base R, interactive graphics are possible, and this opens the

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:46.320
way for new visualizations.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:53.320
And when I say new visualizations, I'm going to use it to play games.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:58.160
My need for interactive graphics started with the game Wordle.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:03.520
This has an intuitive interface with animations and a great user experience, and so I created

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:08.199
a clone of this in R to play.

00:01:08.199 --> 00:01:11.680
This was a text-based interface, which feels a bit clunky.

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:15.919
It does not have the feel or the fluidity of the official game.

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:23.160
And I realized, R gives easy access to text interfaces like Zork on the left, but I want

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:27.839
to play actual video games with sound and color and graphics and actual interaction,

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:31.519
like Pac-Man on the right.

00:01:31.519 --> 00:01:33.599
So I set myself a moonshot goal.

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:38.000
I knew where I wanted to go, but I didn't know how I was going to get there.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.279
And my moonshot was this.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:46.879
I will commit myself to achieving the goal before this year is out of writing and playing

00:01:46.879 --> 00:01:50.360
a video game in R.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:54.680
But this then raises the question, what extra things do I need to know in R in order to

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:58.599
get a game running?

00:01:58.599 --> 00:02:03.239
And I needed to be sure of three things, and I'm going to discuss this with you today,

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:08.320
and that is a fast graphics device for rendering to, a fast way of drawing to this graphics

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:16.119
device to render the game, and mouse and keyboard interaction so we can actually play the game.

00:02:16.119 --> 00:02:21.520
A fast graphics device is essential if I actually want to play games.

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:25.240
I need the graphics to respond at least 30 frames per second.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:29.960
If not, then the games will never run smoothly.

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:34.000
When I say graphics device, I'm referring to the area or window where the plots are

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.720
displayed in R, like the plot window in RStudio.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:41.960
On the Mac, there are a few other graphics devices.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:45.279
There's the Quartz and the X11 device.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:50.960
And I needed to compare them to find out what their speed and response times were.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:55.559
I wrote a very simple benchmark to test how fast a graphics device would respond to a

00:02:55.559 --> 00:02:59.720
simple plotting command.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:05.720
And I was pleasantly surprised that the graphics devices can respond at 30 times per second.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:10.960
In this plot, we see the RStudio and the Quartz device both reaching 30 frames per second,

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:15.919
with the Quartz device about twice as fast as the RStudio device.

00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:19.759
What was really surprising was to see that the X11 device can respond to commands at

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:22.320
over 500 times per second.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:25.880
So yes, R does have a fast graphics device.

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:27.440
We're over the first hurdle.

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:31.919
All graphics devices can respond fast enough, and some graphics devices are faster than

00:03:31.919 --> 00:03:33.039
others.

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:38.759
On the Mac, I'm going to choose to use the X11 device, because it is ridiculously fast.

00:03:38.759 --> 00:03:42.520
Now that I'm confident that the graphics device can respond quickly, I need a fast

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:46.000
way of drawing to that graphics device.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.919
My focus is on pixel-based games, so blocky pixels and polygons, and character sprites

00:03:50.919 --> 00:03:55.679
moving around, like the game of Pac-Man.

00:03:55.679 --> 00:04:00.639
A character sprite, like this cartoon dinosaur, is just a collection of coloured squares,

00:04:00.639 --> 00:04:06.039
and this can be drawn very quickly using just a base R graphics command, gridRect.

00:04:06.039 --> 00:04:15.520
If I draw this, clear the screen, and draw it again, over and over, I can get some animation.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.959
To ensure this drawing system can scale, I'm going to use a common animation technique

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:22.260
known as double buffering.

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:25.679
In double buffering, there is one buffer for drawing, and one buffer for rendering to the

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:26.679
screen.

00:04:26.679 --> 00:04:31.760
And I'm going to implement it in R, like this.

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:36.799
I'm going to create a buffer in R, and then for every frame, draw the game into the buffer.

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:42.279
And when that buffer is ready, copy that buffer into the graphics device.

00:04:42.279 --> 00:04:47.440
For the drawing buffer, I first considered a standard R matrix.

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:54.600
This seems like a pretty good match for representing rectangular array of pixels on the screen.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:59.239
But I ran into some challenges that actually slowed things down, and that is the data ordering

00:04:59.239 --> 00:05:05.200
and the colour representation within a matrix.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:10.320
In a matrix, the data ordering is such that sequential values define a column.

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:16.040
In a graphics device, it wants sequential values to define a row of pixels, so there

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:21.100
is a mismatch between their data representation.

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:23.839
There is also a mismatch in the colour representation.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:29.000
In an R matrix, it would represent colour as a string, but a graphics device actually

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:37.880
wants four numeric values for the four bytes of red, green, blue, and alpha colour channels.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:42.200
So the matrix data layout does not match the graphics device, which means if I was to render

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:46.720
a matrix to the graphics device, then every single time it actually has to do an internal

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:50.320
data conversion, and this is going to slow things down.

00:05:50.799 --> 00:05:55.799
There is actually a second rectangular data structure in R that is more compatible with

00:05:55.799 --> 00:06:02.619
graphics devices, and that is the native raster.

00:06:02.619 --> 00:06:07.480
The native raster is a built-in data structure in R, but it is rarely used.

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:14.779
It's difficult to manipulate from R, but it is highly compatible with graphics devices.

00:06:14.779 --> 00:06:18.799
This table illustrates that the native raster object and the graphics device have the same

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:22.179
data ordering and the same colour representation.

00:06:22.179 --> 00:06:25.480
This means that the native raster objects will be very fast to copy to the graphics

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:32.100
device, as no conversion will need to be done.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:35.200
So my specific double-buffered rendering technique looks like this.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:40.920
I will create a native raster buffer in R, then for every frame, draw the game into that

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:45.679
buffer, and then when it's ready, copy that buffer to the graphics device, just with the

00:06:45.679 --> 00:06:48.359
grid raster command.

00:06:48.359 --> 00:06:51.359
This is a really powerful and scalable technique.

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:56.880
It allows R to render multiple sprites very quickly.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:01.440
As a demonstration that this double-buffering technique works, this is a live capture of

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:05.260
three animated dinosaurs.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:09.839
This is great, but three objects aren't going to make an interesting game, and as I said,

00:07:09.839 --> 00:07:22.559
this method scales, and it scales to 100 dinosaurs, 1,000 dinosaurs, and the limit

00:07:22.559 --> 00:07:29.679
I could reach before the drawing speed dropped below the magic 30 frames per second was 5,000

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:34.320
dinosaurs, and I was really happy with this.

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:36.079
R has a fast way of drawing.

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:40.399
If I use the double-buffering technique, using a native raster as the drawing buffer,

00:07:40.399 --> 00:07:45.320
and then copy that buffer to the graphics device when it's ready.

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:49.559
The final piece of the puzzle is interactivity, an essential element of any game that you

00:07:49.559 --> 00:07:52.600
actually want to play.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:57.040
A standard way you currently might get feedback from the user is to request text using the

00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:00.079
readline command, as shown here.

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:03.559
When calling readline, R cannot do anything else.

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:09.279
It must have the user input before it proceeds to the next line.

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:14.880
In a similar manner, you can get the mouse position using grid locator, but again, while

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:20.880
waiting for the user input, R cannot do anything else.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:24.640
So using this style of interaction would not work for video games.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:28.239
Imagine a game of Pac-Man where the game stopped every time you needed to control the main

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:29.239
character.

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:34.479
It's not going to be an interesting game or very fun.

00:08:34.479 --> 00:08:39.080
We have to change our programming approach and make use of the event-driven capabilities

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:41.280
of our graphics devices.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:46.280
In event-driven interaction, we ask the system to monitor for events, and when they occur,

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:49.359
we ask them to run a particular function.

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:54.119
For those of you familiar with Shiny, it is based on an event-driven framework.

00:08:54.119 --> 00:08:57.679
If you had a button on your web page, you would not run a for loop to check whether

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:00.080
the button has been clicked.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:04.359
You would ask the system, in this case Shiny, that when the button is clicked, please run

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:05.359
my function.

00:09:05.359 --> 00:09:11.119
And that's what the observe event handler is in Shiny.

00:09:11.119 --> 00:09:15.080
Like Shiny, our graphics devices support event-driven interaction.

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:19.039
So we don't need to monitor has the mouse moved or has the keyboard been pressed.

00:09:19.039 --> 00:09:23.320
We can ask the graphics device to monitor for us, and when that event occurs, run a

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:25.679
particular function.

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:30.760
This is all handled by the GRDevice package in the setGraphicsEventHandlers function,

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:34.840
where you can tie functions to particular events.

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.679
The events that you can watch for.

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:38.679
Has the mouse moved?

00:09:38.679 --> 00:09:40.820
And you'll get back the coordinates of the mouse.

00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:43.919
You can monitor for the mouse button being pressed, in which case you will get back the

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:44.919
button number.

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:48.840
You can ask for the keyboard to be monitored, in which case you will get which key has been

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:50.640
pressed.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:54.599
There is one extra event to be monitored, and that is the idle event, when no other

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:57.679
events are happening.

00:09:57.679 --> 00:10:01.239
Consider the idle event to be like the heartbeat of an application.

00:10:01.239 --> 00:10:05.460
When the user is doing something, yes, we handle that input and change our values.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:11.119
But if the user is not doing anything, then we run our idle function, our heartbeat.

00:10:11.119 --> 00:10:16.760
This means that an application skeleton might look something like this.

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:20.700
When the mouse moves, let's update the position of the character on the screen.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:24.159
When the keyboard is pressed, let's run a function that will check whether the user

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:25.719
wants to quit.

00:10:25.719 --> 00:10:33.599
And when the user is otherwise idle, render the next frame in the animation.

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:39.440
As proof that this event-driven interactivity works, I wrote a drum machine in R.

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:43.440
A drum machine is just an electronic instrument that plays drums.

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:48.760
In this drum machine interface, each row represents an instrument, and each button means to play

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:52.419
that instrument at a certain moment in time.

00:10:52.419 --> 00:10:57.059
The events that I have tied to this application are that when the mouse button is pressed,

00:10:57.059 --> 00:11:02.219
we toggle the button underneath the mouse, and when the user is idle, we just continue

00:11:02.219 --> 00:11:04.799
to play the next beat in the sequence.

00:11:04.799 --> 00:11:32.280
This is a short 20-second clip showing the first song I ever composed in R.

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:36.640
This was a lot of fun to program, and great fun to experiment with and compose my own

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:37.640
songs.

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:42.440
And it shows that event-driven interaction does work for what I want for games.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:49.919
I can simultaneously render graphics and play sounds while reacting to user input.

00:11:49.919 --> 00:11:53.580
I now have all the key elements that I need to play a game.

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:56.320
The only thing left is to actually write the game itself.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:12:00.780
Now I'm not going to write a game from scratch, I'm actually going to port an existing game

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:05.260
called Another World.

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:11.719
Another World is an action-adventure side-scrolling platformer released in 1991 for many platforms.

00:12:11.719 --> 00:12:16.020
It has a novel, for its time, virtual machine architecture, which makes it easy to port

00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:20.599
to new systems.

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:23.260
It is, in effect, just a polygon engine.

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:27.219
Rather than storing bitmaps for scenes, it just records a description of how to render

00:12:27.219 --> 00:12:29.599
that scene using polygons.

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:45.400
In this 20-second clip, it is rendering the first scene in the game.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:49.320
And the next scene is rendering a later scene in the game where the main character is having

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:54.320
a drink.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.599
So that's how an individual frame is rendered.

00:12:56.599 --> 00:13:00.640
For the actual gameplay of Another World, I created an R implementation of the virtual

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:01.820
machine.

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:05.919
This was based upon the JavaScript and C versions, which were originally based upon the assembly

00:13:05.919 --> 00:13:10.719
versions for MS-DOS and the Amiga.

00:13:10.719 --> 00:13:14.719
The event-driven game loop is quite simple, and I ask the graphics device when the mouse

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:19.979
or keyboard are used, it calls a function to update the variables in my virtual machine.

00:13:19.979 --> 00:13:24.320
And when the user is otherwise idle, it just executes the next instruction, maybe to draw

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.280
a polygon or play a sound.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:32.400
Which means I can show you the demo of the game.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:38.000
This is a capture running live in R, and to preview what you're going to see, it is the

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.940
typical life of a scientist.

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:44.280
You arrive at work in your Ferrari, you drink at your desk, and then your experiment gets

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:45.320
hit by lightning.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:17.320
With that strike of lightning, you are transported to Another World.

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:21.320
Later in the game, you are captured and you are stuck inside a jail.

00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:25.320
This 10-second demo illustrates keyboard interaction.

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:30.320
By using the left and right arrow keys, I am going to rock the jail and escape.

00:14:30.359 --> 00:14:34.359
That jail escape ends quite abruptly, because I have not yet completed my goal.

00:14:34.359 --> 00:14:38.359
There are still bugs to fix, and a package to release, before I can claim that I have

00:14:38.359 --> 00:14:40.359
a playable game in R.

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:42.359
So, let's get back to the demo.

00:14:42.359 --> 00:14:46.359
This is a capture running live in R, and to preview what you're going to see, it is the

00:14:46.359 --> 00:14:48.359
typical life of a scientist.

00:14:48.359 --> 00:14:51.359
Later in the game, you are captured and you are stuck inside a jail.

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:54.359
Later in the game, you are captured and you are stuck inside a jail.

00:14:54.359 --> 00:14:57.359
Later in the game, you are captured and you are stuck inside a jail.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:00.400
What's next?

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:04.400
Hopefully today with this presentation, I've managed to demonstrate that yes, with careful

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:08.400
use of Base R, interactive graphics are possible, and this opens the way to play games

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:10.400
and new visualizations.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:14.400
I have released packages to document this work, and I encourage you to try them.

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:18.400
If you want to manipulate native RASTA images from R, I have released the NARA package.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:22.400
If you want to manipulate native RASTA images from R, I have released the NARA package.

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:26.440
If you want to manipulate native RASTA images from R, I have released the NARA package.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:30.440
If you want to manipulate native RASTA images from R, I have released the NARA package.

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:34.440
I have released a friendlier wrapper around the event callbacks in the graphics devices.

00:15:34.440 --> 00:15:38.440
This hopefully makes it a little bit easier to use for games.

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:42.440
I know that Matt Dre has used it already for his retro dungeon crawler,

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:46.440
where we can see his blue character being chased by the yellow monster.

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:50.440
where we can see his blue character being chased by the yellow monster.

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:54.479
If you want to see an example of a complex event-driven application,

00:15:54.479 --> 00:15:58.479
I have released the drum machine as a package.

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:02.479
And I hope soon to release the Another World package, so that everyone can play this game.

00:16:06.479 --> 00:16:10.479
R has the capability to write and run interactive graphics in games,

00:16:10.479 --> 00:16:14.479
and I'm fascinated to see what the R community can create.

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:18.479
Game on. Thank you.

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:24.479
Thank you for watching.

